n to the deficient school system (while contributing their &quot;resources&quot; into the deficient school system) may or may not change the school system in the long run - but one thing seems clear, it would not change the school system in time to benefit their own children (whose future is understandably their main concern).  That kind of change takes years and years.  I am concerned by the reference made by the author to parents who chose private education as &quot;bad&quot;; those parents still pay property taxes and income taxes to the county or municipality in which they reside which help to fund the school system (without personally utilizing the school system).  I don't disagree that many school systems in this country are in serious need of overhaul and rejuvenation but the solution that the author suggests does not seem to me to be a feasible one. "/><type4:DocumentMetaData xmi:id="13" sofa="1" begin="0" end="1157" language="en" documentId="3238" isLastSegment="false"/><types:WebArgumentMetadata xmi:id="24" sofa="1" begin="0" end="0" author="Let It Go Today" date="Aug 29, 2013 7:32PM" docType="artcomment" origUrl="http://living.msn.com/family-parenting/the-family-room-blog-post?post=ab228ffc-1e99-4b37-a7b8-0b6a4c3fb240" topic="public-private-schools" thumbsUp="7" thumbsDown="0" origId="3238" notes="" title="Is it wrong to send kids to private school?"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="39" sofa="1" begin="0" end="1157"/><cas:View sofa="1" members="13 24 39"/></xmi:XMI>